     o:['A swimlane partition in an activity diagram','A rectangular frame in a sequence diagram showing conditional or repeated logic','A group of related use cases within the system boundary','A package in a class diagram containing related classes']},
    {t:'Define the term', q:'Define: Scope creep', c:2, e:'Scope creep is the gradual expansion of a project beyond its original agreed scope, typically caused by vague requirements or unchecked stakeholder requests. A clearly defined system boundary helps prevent it.',
     o:['A design smell caused by too many inheritance levels','A testing failure that appears only in production environments','The gradual expansion of a project beyond its originally agreed scope','A form of coupling where two classes share too many associations']},
    {t:'Define the term', q:'Define: Feature envy', c:1, e:'Feature envy is a design smell where a class has operations that mostly access data from another class. This suggests those operations belong in the other class.',
     o:['A user requirement that is desirable but not mandatory','A design smell where a class uses mostly data from another class','A use case that extends a base use case with optional behaviour','An over-engineered inheritance hierarchy']},

    // TYPE 2: Identify the term from the definition
    {t:'Identify the term', q:'Which term matches this definition? "A role outside the system boundary that interacts with the system."', c:1, e:'An actor is anything outside the system boundary that interacts with it — a human user, external system, or time trigger. The term stakeholder is broader and includes people who do not directly use the system.',
     o:['Use case','Actor','Stakeholder','System administrator']},
    {t:'Identify the term', q:'Which term matches this definition? "The degree to which a class is tightly focused on a single, well-defined responsibility."', c:2, e:'Cohesion measures single-purpose focus. High cohesion means the class does one thing well. Coupling, by contrast, measures dependency between classes.',
     o:['Coupling','Abstraction','Cohesion','Encapsulation']},
    {t:'Identify the term', q:'Which term matches this definition? "A dashed arrow in a sequence diagram representing the completion of a synchronous call."', c:2, e:'Return messages are drawn as dashed arrows pointing back to the original caller. They represent the response from a synchronous operation and can be labelled with the return value.',
     o:['Asynchronous message','Create message','Return message','Self-call']},
    {t:'Identify the term', q:'Which term matches this definition? "A thick bar in an activity diagram that waits for all parallel branches to complete before continuing."', c:3, e:'A join node synchronises all incoming parallel flows. Every parallel path must complete before the outgoing flow can proceed. It is the counterpart of the fork node.',
     o:['Decision node','Fork node','Flow final node','Join node']},
    {t:'Identify the term', q:'Which term matches this definition? "A table that maps each requirement to the design artefacts that implement it."', c:1, e:'A traceability matrix makes gaps immediately visible — a requirement with no corresponding design element will not be built. It also supports impact analysis when requirements change.',
     o:['Requirements specification','Traceability matrix','Integration checklist','Design rationale document']},
    {t:'Identify the term', q:'Which term matches this definition? "A class with many attributes, operations, and associations to most other classes."', c:2, e:'A god class violates the Single Responsibility Principle. It becomes a bottleneck — hard to understand, test, and change. The fix is to extract focused classes from it.',
     o:['Abstract class','Base class','God class','Utility class']},
    {t:'Identify the term', q:'Which term matches this definition? "A software process model that uses short iterative development cycles and welcomes changing requirements."', c:2, e:'Agile is built around short iterations (sprints), continuous stakeholder collaboration, and working software delivered frequently. Waterfall is sequential and resists change once phases are closed.',
     o:['Waterfall','Spiral','Agile','V-Model']},
    {t:'Identify the term', q:'Which term matches this definition? "A rectangular frame in a sequence diagram labelled with an operator such as alt, opt, or loop."', c:1, e:'Combined fragments are used to show conditional and repeated logic within a sequence diagram. The operator in the top-left corner defines the semantics: alt = alternatives, opt = optional, loop = repeated.',
     o:['System boundary','Combined fragment','Swimlane','Activation block']},
    {t:'Identify the term', q:'Which term matches this definition? "The ability of a system to handle growth in load, features, or development team size."', c:3, e:'Scalability covers three dimensions: load (more users/data), feature (new functionality without redesign), and team (multiple developers working independently). Low coupling is essential for all three.',
     o:['Reliability','Maintainability','Usability','Scalability']},
    {t:'Identify the term', q:'Which term matches this definition? "Documentation explaining why a design decision was made, including options considered and trade-offs accepted."', c:1, e:'Design rationale captures the reasoning behind decisions — not just what was decided, but why. It prevents future maintainers from unknowingly revisiting decisions already made.',
     o:['System specification','Design rationale','Requirements document','Test plan']},
    {t:'Identify the term', q:'Which term matches this definition? "A constraint specifying how many instances of one class can be associated with instances of another."', c:2, e:'Multiplicity is written at each end of an association line. Common values: 1 (exactly one), 0..1 (optional), 1..* (one or more), 0..* or * (zero or more).',
     o:['Navigability','Cardinality','Multiplicity','Association degree']},

    // TYPE 3: Key difference between A and B
    {t:'Explain the difference', q:'What is the key difference between «include» and «extend»?', c:1, e:'«include» models mandatory behaviour — the sub-flow always runs. «extend» models optional behaviour — it runs only when a specific condition is met. The arrow direction also differs: «include» points from base to included; «extend» points from extending to base.',
     o:['«include» is used between actors; «extend» is used between use cases','«include» models mandatory sub-flows; «extend» models optional behaviour under a condition','«include» adds optional behaviour; «extend» adds mandatory sub-flows','There is no functional difference — they are interchangeable in most diagrams']},
    {t:'Explain the difference', q:'What is the key difference between aggregation and composition?', c:2, e:'In aggregation, parts can exist independently of the whole (hollow diamond). In composition, parts cannot exist without the whole — destroying the whole destroys the parts (filled diamond). The diamond is at the whole end in both cases.',
     o:['Aggregation uses a filled diamond; composition uses a hollow diamond','Aggregation is used for inheritance; composition is used for associations','In aggregation, parts can exist independently; in composition, they cannot exist without the whole','Aggregation uses a dashed line; composition uses a solid line']},
    {t:'Explain the difference', q:'What is the key difference between a decision node and a fork node in an activity diagram?', c:1, e:'A decision node (diamond) sends the flow down exactly one outgoing path based on a guard condition — it is a choice. A fork node (thick bar) sends the flow down all outgoing paths simultaneously — it starts parallel execution.',
     o:['A decision node is round; a fork node is rectangular','A decision node chooses one path; a fork node starts all paths simultaneously in parallel','A decision node starts parallel flows; a fork node selects a single path','They represent the same concept with different visual styles in different versions of UML']},
    {t:'Explain the difference', q:'What is the key difference between cohesion and coupling?', c:2, e:'Cohesion and coupling are related but distinct. Cohesion is an internal measure — how focused is this class? Coupling is an external measure — how much does this class depend on others? The goal is high cohesion AND low coupling.',
     o:['Cohesion measures class size; coupling measures the number of methods','Cohesion and coupling are the same concept described from different perspectives','Cohesion measures how focused a class is; coupling measures how much it depends on other classes','Cohesion applies to methods; coupling applies only to classes']},
    {t:'Explain the difference', q:'What is the key difference between a synchronous and an asynchronous message?', c:1, e:'A synchronous message (filled arrowhead) causes the sender to wait for a response before continuing — like a standard method call. An asynchronous message (open arrowhead) lets the sender continue immediately, without waiting.',
     o:['A synchronous message is drawn as a dashed arrow; an asynchronous message is solid','A synchronous message sender waits for a response; an asynchronous sender continues immediately','Synchronous messages always carry a labelled return value; asynchronous messages never do','There is no visual difference — only the label on the arrow distinguishes them']},
    {t:'Explain the difference', q:'What is the key difference between an activity diagram and a sequence diagram?', c:1, e:'An activity diagram models processes and workflows — the steps, decisions, and flows — without necessarily specifying which objects perform them. A sequence diagram models interactions between specific named objects and the messages they exchange.',
     o:['Activity diagrams show object interactions; sequence diagrams show process flows','Activity diagrams model processes and workflows; sequence diagrams model interactions between specific objects','Activity diagrams are used only by developers; sequence diagrams are for business analysts','Activity diagrams cannot show decision points; sequence diagrams can use alt fragments instead']},
    {t:'Explain the difference', q:'What is the key difference between an activity final node and a flow final node?', c:1, e:'The activity final node (bullseye) terminates the entire activity — all active flows stop. The flow final node (circle with X) terminates only the one branch it is on — other parallel branches continue unaffected.',
     o:['An activity final node ends a single branch; a flow final node ends the entire activity','An activity final node ends the entire activity; a flow final node ends only one branch','They are visually identical and functionally equivalent in standard UML','An activity final node is used in sequence diagrams; a flow final node is for class diagrams']},
    {t:'Explain the difference', q:'What is the key difference between a functional and a non-functional requirement?', c:1, e:'Functional requirements describe what the system must do — specific features and behaviours. Non-functional requirements describe how well it must perform — qualities such as speed, security, reliability, and usability.',
     o:['Functional requirements are written by developers; non-functional requirements by managers','Functional requirements describe features the system provides; non-functional describe how well it performs them','Functional requirements apply to the whole system; non-functional apply only to the user interface','Non-functional requirements are optional extras; functional requirements are always mandatory']},
    {t:'Explain the difference', q:'What is the key difference between inheritance and composition?', c:0, e:'Inheritance expresses an is-a relationship — a child class is a specialised kind of parent class. Composition expresses a strong has-a relationship — the whole contains parts that cannot exist independently. Choosing the wrong one is a common design error.',
     o:['Inheritance expresses an is-a relationship; composition expresses a strong has-a relationship where parts cannot exist without the whole','Inheritance models whole-part relationships; composition models type hierarchies','Inheritance uses a filled diamond; composition uses a hollow triangle arrowhead','There is no meaningful difference — both model relationships between two classes']},
    {t:'Explain the difference', q:'What is the key difference between the Waterfall and Agile methodologies?', c:2, e:'Waterfall is sequential — each phase completes before the next begins, and changes are costly once a phase is closed. Agile is iterative — it works in short cycles, welcomes changing requirements, and delivers working software frequently.',
     o:['Waterfall is used for small projects; Agile is used for large enterprise systems','Waterfall uses UML diagrams throughout; Agile does not use UML at all','Waterfall is sequential with phases completed in order; Agile is iterative with short cycles and evolving requirements','Waterfall produces working software faster; Agile produces better technical documentation']},
    {t:'Explain the difference', q:'What is the key difference between a structural and a behavioural UML diagram?', c:0, e:'Structural diagrams (e.g. class diagram) show what exists in the system at a point in time — static elements. Behavioural diagrams (e.g. activity, sequence) show how the system behaves over time — actions, messages, and flows.',
     o:['Structural diagrams show what exists statically; behavioural diagrams show how the system acts over time','Structural diagrams are used by developers; behavioural diagrams are for business analysts only','Structural diagrams model processes; behavioural diagrams model data and attributes','There is no meaningful distinction — all UML diagrams are treated equivalently']},
    {t:'Explain the difference', q:'What is the key difference between a use case diagram and a class diagram?', c:0, e:'A use case diagram shows user goals and system scope — what users want to do. A class diagram shows the static structure needed to support those goals — the classes, attributes, operations, and relationships that implement the system.',
     o:['A use case diagram shows user goals; a class diagram shows the static structure that supports them','A use case diagram is for developers; a class diagram is for clients and managers','A use case diagram shows classes; a class diagram shows actors and their interactions','A use case diagram is more technically detailed than a class diagram']}
  ];

  var remaining = [];

  function refill() {
    remaining = Q.map(function(_, i) { return i; });
  }

  function pickNext() {
    if (remaining.length === 0) refill();
    var ri = Math.floor(Math.random() * remaining.length);
    var qi = remaining.splice(ri, 1)[0];
    return Q[qi];
  }

  var current = null;
  var answered = false;
  var score = 0;
  var total = 0;

  function umlqbNext() {
    current = pickNext();
    answered = false;

    var badgeColors = { 'Define the term': '#ff8c00', 'Identify the term': '#4a90d9', 'Explain the difference': '#9c6cd4' };
    var badge = document.getElementById('umlqb-badge');
    badge.textContent = current.t;
    badge.style.color = badgeColors[current.t] || '#888';

    document.getElementById('umlqb-q').textContent = current.q;

    var html = '';
    current.o.forEach(function(opt, i) {
      html += '<label class="quiz-option" style="cursor:pointer;">' +
        '<input type="radio" name="umlqb-r" value="' + i + '"> ' + opt + '</label>';
    });
    document.getElementById('umlqb-opts').innerHTML = html;

    document.getElementById('umlqb-check-btn').style.display = '';
    document.getElementById('umlqb-feedback').style.display = 'none';
    document.getElementById('umlqb-feedback').innerHTML = '';

    var seen = Q.length - remaining.length;
    document.getElementById('umlqb-counter').textContent =
      seen + ' of ' + Q.length + ' questions seen this session' +
      (remaining.length === 0 ? ' — full set complete, resetting' : '');
  }

  function umlqbCheck() {
    if (answered) return;
    var sel = document.querySelector('input[name="umlqb-r"]:checked');
    if (!sel) return;
    answered = true;
    total++;
    var chosen = parseInt(sel.value);
    var ok = chosen === current.c;
    if (ok) score++;

    var fb = document.getElementById('umlqb-feedback');
    fb.style.display = 'block';
    fb.innerHTML =
      '<div class="p-3" style="border-radius:0.375rem; background:' +
        (ok ? 'rgba(46,204,113,0.08); border-left:3px solid #2ecc71;' : 'rgba(231,76,60,0.08); border-left:3px solid #e74c3c;') + '">' +
      '<p class="mb-1 fw-semibold" style="color:' + (ok ? '#2ecc71' : '#e74c3c') + ';">' +
        (ok ? '\u2713 Correct' : '\u2717 Incorrect') + '</p>' +
      '<p class="mb-0 small" style="color:#ccc;">' + current.e + '</p>' +
      (ok ? '' : '<p class="mt-2 mb-0 small" style="color:#aaa;">Correct answer: <strong style="color:#ddd;">' + current.o[current.c] + '</strong></p>') +
      '</div>';

    document.getElementById('umlqb-check-btn').style.display = 'none';
    document.getElementById('umlqb-counter').textContent =
      'Score: ' + score + ' / ' + total + ' \u2022 ' +
      (Q.length - remaining.length) + ' of ' + Q.length + ' seen this session';
  }

  window.umlqbNext = umlqbNext;
  window.umlqbCheck = umlqbCheck;
}());
</script>

{% endcall %}


{# ══ Activity 7 — Individual / Pair / Group ═══════════════════════════ #}

{% set activityTabs = [
  {id: "ind",   label: "Individual"},
  {id: "pair",  label: "Pair"},
  {id: "group", label: "Group"}
] %}

{% call activitySection(7, "Activities", "people") %}

{% call tabSet("unit10-act7", activityTabs) %}
  <div class="tab-pane fade show active" id="unit10-act7-ind" role="tabpanel">
    <p class="fw-semibold">Individual task</p>
    <p>
      Review the complete set of UML diagrams you have built in this course. Choose one
      diagram and write a structured critique using the describe-evaluate-justify-suggest framework.
    </p>
    <p>Your critique should:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Identify at least <strong>one strength</strong> with evidence and justification</li>
      <li>Identify at least <strong>one weakness</strong> with evidence and a specific, feasible suggestion for improvement</li>
      <li>Apply at least <strong>two quality criteria</strong> (e.g. maintainability and reliability)</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
  <div class="tab-pane fade" id="unit10-act7-pair" role="tabpanel">
    <p class="fw-semibold">Pair task</p>
    <p>Exchange critiques with a partner and evaluate the critique itself:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Is each point of criticism <strong>specific</strong>? (Does it name an element?)</li>
      <li>Is each point <strong>justified with evidence</strong>? (Is there something observable in the diagram to support it?)</li>
      <li>Is the suggested improvement <strong>feasible</strong> and <strong>clearly described</strong>?</li>
      <li>Does the critique go beyond description to genuine analysis?</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Identify the strongest part of your partner's critique — and the one part that could
      be made more analytical. Explain both.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="tab-pane fade" id="unit10-act7-group" role="tabpanel">
    <p class="fw-semibold">Group task — design debate</p>
    <p>
      Select one design decision your group made during Units 5 or 8 — one where alternatives
      were discussed or where the right choice was not obvious.
    </p>
    <p>Reconstruct the debate:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>What were the alternatives?</li>
      <li>What criteria did you use to decide (implicitly or explicitly)?</li>
      <li>What trade-offs did you accept?</li>
      <li>Having now completed all 10 units — would you make the same decision? Why or why not?</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      This final task asks you to think like a senior engineer: not just "what did we do?" but
      "was it the right thing to do, and what have we learned?"
    </p>
  </div>
{% endcall %}

{% endcall %}


{# ══ Review ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ #}

{% call reviewSection() %}

<div class="accordion mb-3" id="unit10-review">
  {% call accordion("rev-10-a", "Summary: What are the five quality criteria from this unit?") %}
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Maintainability</strong> — how easily can the system be changed safely?</li>
    <li><strong>Scalability</strong> — can the system handle more load, more features, or more developers?</li>
    <li><strong>Usability</strong> — does the design genuinely support user goals?</li>
    <li><strong>Reliability</strong> — does the design account for failure and error conditions?</li>
    <li><strong>Security</strong> — does the design enforce appropriate authorisation and data protection?</li>
  </ul>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("rev-10-b", "Summary: How does this course connect — the full spiral?") %}
  <p>
    This course was designed as a spiral: each unit revisited and deepened earlier work.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Units 1–2</strong> — the foundation: what is software engineering and how do we capture requirements?</li>
    <li><strong>Units 3–7</strong> — the four diagram types, each building on the last: use cases → class structure → behaviour → processes</li>
    <li><strong>Unit 8</strong> — integration: ensuring all diagrams form a coherent, consistent whole</li>
    <li><strong>Unit 9</strong> — communication: presenting and explaining designs to different audiences</li>
    <li><strong>Unit 10</strong> — evaluation: applying critical judgement to assess the quality of any design</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A software engineer who can do all five of these things — specify, model, integrate,
    communicate, and evaluate — is equipped to work effectively on real systems.
    That is the goal this course was designed to support.
  </p>
  {% endcall %}
</div>

<p class="mt-3 small" style="color:#e0e0e0;">
  <i class="bi bi-check-circle"></i>
  You have completed <strong>UML for Software Engineering</strong>.
  Return to the <a href="{{ '/courses/uml/' | url }}">course home page</a>.
</p>
{% endcall %}
